definition.value: A quantitative measurement of xenobiotics (a chemical foreign to the body) present in gastric fluid.
A quantitative measurement of xenobiotics (a chemical foreign to the body) present in a hair sample.
A medical examination performed using of magnetic resonance imaging to image the bony pelvis.
Use of an imaging test that uses small amounts of radiation to produce pictures of lymphatic part of lymphoid system.

A laboratory test in which blood, taken from the patient, is inoculated into bottles containing culture media to determine whether infection-causing microorganisms (bacteria or fungi) are present in the patient's bloodstream.
Inspection of stomach using an endoscope.
An x-ray of blood vessels after a contrast dye is added intraveniously.
Is an imaging procedure often using a specific contrast dye for evaluation of pelvic floor, anorectal muscle contractions and relaxation (sphincters), and certain structural abnormalities.
A procedure where fluid is removed from the abdomen using a needle.
A comprehensive set of tests designed to assess all aspects of a child's development, including cognition, language, motor, and social skills.
Inspection of duodenum using an endoscope.
Use of an imaging test that uses small amounts of radiation to produce pictures of forelimb.
The use of computed tomography to produce images of structures of the heart.
A motility study to assess motor function of the upper esophageal sphincter, esophageal body and lower esophageal sphincter.
A quantitative measurement of metabolites present in a stool sample.

A radiographic examination of the upper gastrointestinal tract in which the esophagus, stomach, and duodenum are made visible by barium or a water-soluble contrast administered orally prior to the examination.

value.value: A combined endoscopic and fluoroscopic procedure in which an upper endoscope is led into a second part of the duodenum, making it possible for passage of other tools via the major duodenal papilla into the biliary and pancreatic ducts. Contrast material may be injected in these ducts, allowing for radiologic visualization and therapeutic interventions when indicated.

definition.value: Use of an imaging test that uses small amounts of radiation to produce pictures of vertebral column.
A medical examination performed using of magnetic resonance imaging to image the muscle organ.
Use of an imaging test that uses small amounts of radiation to produce pictures of hip.
The use of ultrasound to produce images of structures in the ovary.
Assessment of the degree or kind of protein glycosylation (covalent attachment of a carbohydrate moiety to a protein).
A technique for counting, examining and sorting microscopic particles suspended in a stream of fluid. NCIT:C16585

Reproductive endocrinology and infertility is a surgical subspecialty of obstetrics and gynecology that trains physicians in reproductive medicine addressing hormonal functioning as it pertains to reproduction as well as the issue of infertility.
A quantitative measurement of a particular hormone present in a sample.
A test to determine the electrical conduction of the motor and sensory nerves of the human body.
The time taken for neural impulses to travel through the central nervous system on their way to the target muscles. PMID: 24112910
The use of computed tomography to produce images of structures of the bony pelvis.
A quantitative measurement of a particular hormone present in a sample of urine.

A technique that combines EEG and EMG to assess myoclonus; it use electromyography (EMG) electrodes for the arms or legs, and correlates averaged EEG responses with EMG bursts used as a trigger. PMID: 1464676
The transmission electron microscope (TEM) is a diagnostic tool to screen human tissues at high magnification to visualize the ultrastructural level.

A procedure where a dental professional who was not previously involved in a patient's treatment, reviews a patient's medical history, examines the patient, and makes recommendations as to care and treatment.

Measurement of somatosensory evoked potentials (SEPs), which reflect the electrical activity of the brain that results from the stimulation of touch. SEP monitoring may be employed intraoperatively to identify, and ideally, avoid impending permanent damage to neurologic structures. PMID: 31335078

In the perchlorate discharge test, first radioactive iodine is administered, sufficient time is allowed to pass so that the radioactive iodine is captured by the thyroid, and then, perchlorate is administered orally. The perchlorate displaces non-organified iodide from the thyroid. The perchlorate discharge test is considered positive (abnormal) if there is an abnormally rapid loss of radioactive iodine from the thyroid.
An assay of the physiology of natural killer (NK) cells.

Dysmorphology refers to the study of human congenital malformations and syndromes. A dysmorphology evaluation includes an assessment of facial features and also features of the entire body especially with respect to manifestations of hereditary (Mendelian) disease).
The determination of the amount of reactive oxygen species present in the sample.
A determination of the structure of leukocyte.
A determination of the structure of megakaryocyte.
Use of an imaging test that uses small amounts of radiation to produce pictures of ankle joint.
Quantification of sperm cell characteristics, including morphology, motility, and number.
A complement test is a blood test that measures the activity of one or more proteins that make up the complement system in blood circulation.
The test measures the T cell responses to antigens of common infections as well as to mitogens, allowing detection of deficiencies in this arm of the immune response.

A complete evaluation of the respiratory system including patient history, physical examinations, and tests of pulmonary function. The primary purpose of pulmonary function testing is to identify the severity of pulmonary impairment.
Examination by a doctor who specializes in the care of newborn babies.
A test to determine if cells are undergoing programmed cell death.

value.value: A contrast-enhanced radiographic study commonly used to assess structural characteristics of the entire esophagus.

definition.value: Computed tomography (CT) examination of the kidneys, ureters and bladder following administration of intravenous contrast material.
Determination of serum uric acid following the administration of an oral bolus of fructose to assess the ability of an individual to digest fructose.
Use of an imaging test that uses small amounts of radiation to produce pictures of cervical region of vertebral column.
